---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const svpBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Senior VP &amp; VP Executive Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Senior VP &amp; VP mortgage from a lender who reads RSU vesting, annual bonus formulas, and promotion-track compensation.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Senior VPs and VPs at public companies carry a compensation file that&rsquo;s the second-most-complex W-2 in American corporate life: a base salary that&rsquo;s typically 35&ndash;55% of total comp, restricted stock units (RSUs) and performance stock units (PSUs) vesting on 3&ndash;4 year graded schedules, annual cash bonuses tied to individual and corporate performance metrics, sometimes long-term incentive plan (LTIP) cash payouts, often retention RSUs granted at promotion, and unvested-equity "golden handcuffs" that anchor mobility decisions. Generalist lenders see the base salary line and discount the equity. We read the grant letters, the bonus formula, the vesting schedule, the promotion-track context, and the 12-to-24-month vest history &mdash; and qualify you on the full comp package including equity.</p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Schedule a call with Jim</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in SVP/VP equity-comp &amp; promotion-track mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/3184360/pexels-photo-3184360.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Senior VP in corporate strategy session" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Senior+VP';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$102K</div>
            <div class="stat-label">BLS general &amp; operations managers May 2024 median (corporate SVPs significantly higher)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">35&ndash;55%</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Base salary as % of SVP total comp (vs 7% for S&amp;P 500 CEOs)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">12 mo</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Time-based RSU vest history required by Fannie Mae for qualifying income</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">1</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Specialist who reads your grant letters &amp; bonus formula before we quote</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/3184292/pexels-photo-3184292.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Corporate conference room with senior leadership team" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Senior+VP';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies SVPs and VPs on the full comp package &mdash; <strong>not just the base salary that&rsquo;s half of what you actually earn</strong>. A newly-promoted SVP with a sign-on RSU grant and prior VP-level bonus history, an established Division President with five years of consistent RSU vesting and a cash LTIP cycle, a Group SVP with P&amp;L responsibility and a six-figure annual bonus, and an SVP on the cusp of a C-suite promotion managing golden-handcuffs timing each get qualified using the methods that fit their stage. We pick the right door before we quote. Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other executive paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">corporate executives mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; SVP / VP mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every senior VP or VP should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">$102,950</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">BLS May 2024 median for general and operations managers (closest SOC). Corporate SVP/VP total comp typically $300K&ndash;$1.2M, with equity often equaling base &mdash; see <a href="https://www.bls.gov/ooh/management/top-executives.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BLS Top Executives OOH</a> and <a href="https://www.bls.gov/oes/current/oes111021.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BLS OEWS SOC 11-1021</a>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">12 / 24 mo</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Minimum vest history required by Fannie Mae: <strong>12 months for time-based RSUs</strong>, <strong>24 months for performance-based PSUs</strong>. See <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae Selling Guide B3-3.1-01</a> variable income rules.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">2-year bonus avg</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Annual cash bonus &mdash; often 20&ndash;40% of SVP total comp &mdash; qualifies on a <strong>two-year average</strong> under Fannie Mae variable-income rules. Documented via W-2 history, employment letter bonus formula, and comp committee minutes.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">200-day MA</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Stock-price valuation method Fannie Mae uses for RSU income; <a href="https://guide.freddiemac.com/app/guide/section/5303.4" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Freddie Mac</a> uses the 52-week average. Both require the company to be publicly traded for a comparable lookback period.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your SVP/VP tenure</div>
        <h2>SVP / VP mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each SVP/VP stage has its own qualifying logic. A newly-promoted VP one year in has a different mortgage path than a 7-year Group SVP with significant unvested equity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Newly-promoted VP (Year 1&ndash;2)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Just promoted from Director. First RSU grant. New bonus structure."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base $200K&ndash;$350K, first RSU grant not yet 12-month vested</li>
            <li>Qualifies on base + prior Director-level W-2 with bonus history</li>
            <li>Conventional conforming or low-jumbo, bank-statement Non-QM bridge</li>
            <li>Often refinance after 12-month vest history matures</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See newly-promoted mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established VP (Years 2&ndash;5)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"VP for 3 years. RSUs vesting annually. Annual bonus on 2-year average."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base $250K&ndash;$450K + $100K&ndash;$300K annual equity vest + cash bonus</li>
            <li>Full RSU income qualifying with 24-month history</li>
            <li>Conventional jumbo with base + RSU 200-day MA</li>
            <li>Bonus 2-year average adds substantial qualifying income</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See established VP mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Senior VP / Division President</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"SVP with P&amp;L responsibility. LTIP cycle active. Multi-year RSU grants."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base $400K&ndash;$700K + significant annual equity + cash LTIP cycle</li>
            <li>Multi-year LTIP cycle qualifies if 6-year (two-cycle) history exists</li>
            <li>Jumbo or low-end super-jumbo loans typical</li>
            <li>Often paired with second home or rental property purchase</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See SVP / Division President mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Group SVP (multi-division)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Group SVP overseeing 2&ndash;4 divisions. Equity heavy. Pre-C-suite track."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Base $500K&ndash;$900K + heavy equity comp + retention grants</li>
            <li>Unvested equity at any moment often $1M&ndash;$3M</li>
            <li>Super-jumbo eligibility on full comp package</li>
            <li>Pledged-asset loans useful when avoiding concentrated stock liquidation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See Group SVP mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">SVP transitioning (promotion or exit)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"On track for C-suite promotion or considering external move. Golden handcuffs."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Unvested equity creating timing decisions for external moves</li>
            <li>Garden leave / non-compete may create gap-period qualifying issues</li>
            <li>Sign-on bonuses and retention grants from acquirer common</li>
            <li>Bridge financing or asset-depletion may apply during transitions</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See transition mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your SVP/VP mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every SVP/VP file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on tenure, comp mix, employer public/private status, and whether you&rsquo;re newly promoted or established.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Base W-2 + RSU vest income (Fannie Mae 200-day MA)</h3>
      <p>The dominant case for established public-company SVPs and VPs. Base salary is W-2 wages. RSU income is calculated by taking vested shares over the trailing 12&ndash;24 months, valued at the <strong>200-day moving average</strong> of the company stock price. The result divided by the months in the lookback produces monthly qualifying income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae Selling Guide B3-3.1-01</a>. We pull the brokerage statement, the vesting schedule, the grant letter, and the W-2 to assemble this calculation properly.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Base + annual cash bonus 2-year average</h3>
      <p>For SVPs and VPs where annual cash bonus is a larger relative component than equity (financial services, smaller public companies, private-company executives). Bonus is reported on the W-2 alongside base. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, variable income with a two-year history qualifies on the two-year average. We document the bonus formula via your employment letter or comp committee minutes, the prior W-2s showing the historical bonus pattern, and the trend. Declining bonuses face downward adjustment; growing bonuses cannot be projected forward (the two-year average is the ceiling).</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; LTIP cash payouts as variable income</h3>
      <p>For senior SVPs and Division Presidents with cash-based long-term incentive plans on 3-year payout cycles. These show on the W-2 in payout years as lumpy income. A two-cycle (6-year) history of LTIP payouts qualifies as continuing income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> variable-income rules. We document the LTIP plan document, the historical W-2 payouts, and the formula. Without the multi-cycle pattern, lenders treat LTIP as one-time and exclude.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Bank-statement (Non-QM) during promotion or transition</h3>
      <p>For newly-promoted VPs without 12-month RSU vest history, or SVPs in role transitions where the prior W-2 isn&rsquo;t representative of current comp. <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/43/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CFPB Reg Z&rsquo;s Ability-to-Repay rule</a> permits non-QM lending with compensating factors. We qualify on 12 or 24 months of personal bank deposits with an expense-ratio adjustment (typically 50&ndash;75% of deposits count as qualifying income). The result often beats the W-2 during promotion or sign-on periods.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/3184360/pexels-photo-3184360.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on an SVP/VP file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income components that show up consistently on SVP/VP files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore or mis-categorize. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to know what to ask for.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">RSU vesting income (still the big one)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">For public-company SVPs and VPs, RSU income typically represents 30&ndash;50% of total comp. With <strong>12+ months of time-based vest history</strong> (or 24+ for performance-based PSUs), the income qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> using the 200-day moving average. Generalist lenders see the base salary on the W-2 and stop reading; they miss the largest variable-comp component on the file.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Annual cash bonus 2-year average</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">For SVP/VP files, annual cash bonus is often <strong>20&ndash;40% of total comp</strong> and qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae variable-income rules</a> with a two-year history. We document the bonus formula via the employment letter or comp committee minutes. Generalist lenders often treat the bonus as discretionary one-off income and exclude it &mdash; missing 25%+ of qualifying income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Sign-on bonus and retention RSU grants</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Newly-promoted or laterally-recruited SVPs often receive sign-on bonus payments ($100K&ndash;$1M) and retention RSU grants on 3&ndash;4 year vesting schedules. The sign-on is one-time and doesn&rsquo;t qualify as continuing income; the retention RSUs do qualify once the 12-month vest history exists. Underwriters often conflate the two and exclude both.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Long-term incentive plan (LTIP) cash payouts</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Senior SVPs and Division Presidents often receive cash LTIP payouts every 3 years against performance metrics. A 6-year (two-cycle) pattern qualifies as continuing income. <a href="https://www.sec.gov/rules/final/2006/33-8732a.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">SEC executive comp disclosure rules</a> require LTIP detail in DEF 14A proxy statements for NEOs. Generalist lenders without the multi-cycle pattern documentation treat LTIP as one-time and exclude.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Employee stock purchase plan (ESPP) discount</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Many public-company executives participate in ESPPs allowing purchase of company stock at a 15% discount with look-back pricing. The discount qualifies as compensation income on the W-2 in the purchase year. Under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc427" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">IRS Topic 427</a>, ESPP discount is W-2 wage in qualifying-disposition years. Lenders frequently miss this $5K&ndash;$50K of additional qualifying income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">401(k) employer match &amp; profit-sharing</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">SVPs and VPs typically receive employer 401(k) match (often 4&ndash;6% of base) plus profit-sharing contributions ($10K&ndash;$30K annually). Under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/plan-participant-employee/401k-resource-guide-plan-participants-general-distribution-rules" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">IRS 401(k) guidance</a>, these are deferred compensation but represent real annual comp value documented on the W-2 box 12. Lenders consider them in net-worth and reserve calculations, not directly as qualifying income, but they support the overall financial-strength narrative.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; Match the program to your SVP/VP stage</div>
        <h2>Which loan program fits your SVP/VP mortgage situation.</h2>
        <p>Seven loan-program categories cover essentially every SVP/VP purchase or refinance. The mix tilts conforming-to-jumbo at this income tier (less super-jumbo than C-suite).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="loan-program-grid">

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Conventional Conforming</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Newly-promoted VPs or smaller-company SVPs</li>
            <li>5&ndash;20% down, loan limits up to $766,550 (FL conforming) for 2024-25</li>
            <li>Best rates available; full Fannie/Freddie underwriting on RSU and bonus</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Year 1&ndash;2 VPs at conforming limit</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Conventional Jumbo</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Established VPs and SVPs with base + equity income above conforming</li>
            <li>10&ndash;20% down typical, $766,550&ndash;$2M loan range</li>
            <li>Rate often within 0.25% of conforming for clean files</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Method 1 (base + RSU + bonus)</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Super-Jumbo Portfolio</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Group SVPs and Division Presidents at $2M+ loan size</li>
            <li>15&ndash;25% down typical, relationship-driven underwriting</li>
            <li>Custom rate sheet, often paired with private banking</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Group SVP / Division President</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Pledged-Asset Loan</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>SVPs avoiding liquidation of concentrated company stock</li>
            <li>Securities portfolio pledged against the mortgage</li>
            <li>Often $0 down via securities lien</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Equity-heavy comp / golden handcuffs</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Bank-Statement Non-QM</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Newly-promoted VPs without 12-month RSU vest history</li>
            <li>12 or 24 months of personal deposits at 50&ndash;75% counting</li>
            <li>Rate 0.5&ndash;1.0% higher than conforming</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Promotion-window financing</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Asset-Depletion Non-QM</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>SVPs with significant liquid net worth from prior equity sales</li>
            <li>Assets amortized over 360 months as implied income</li>
            <li>Specialty Non-QM lenders only</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Transition periods</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">VA Loan</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>SVPs and VPs with U.S. military service</li>
            <li>0% down, no PMI, rate competitive with conventional</li>
            <li>Self-funded VA jumbo for higher loan amounts</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Veteran executive borrowers</div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #6: INDUSTRY CONTEXT ============ -->
  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Why this mortgage is harder than it should be</div>
        <h2>The SVP/VP mortgage in context: 6 forces shaping how senior executives qualify.</h2>
        <p>The reason a generalist lender struggles with an SVP/VP file is the same reason C-suite files trip lenders up: corporate comp combines equity grants, multi-year deferrals, and contingent components that don&rsquo;t map onto W-2 underwriting. The mix at SVP level is different from C-suite, but the underwriting principles are similar.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Force 1 &mdash; The base-to-equity ratio shifts with each promotion</h3>
      <p>At entry-level Director, base salary is typically 70&ndash;80% of total comp. At VP, base drops to 55&ndash;65% with RSUs and bonus filling the rest. At SVP, base is 35&ndash;55%. By C-suite, base is 7&ndash;30%. <a href="https://www.sec.gov/rules/final/2006/33-8732a.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SEC executive comp disclosure rules</a> require detailed proxy reporting of all comp components, and the <a href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/econres/scfindex.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Federal Reserve Survey of Consumer Finances</a> documents the wealth-concentration trend among top earners. Each promotion shifts the qualifying picture; the lender who handled your Director mortgage may not be set up for your SVP mortgage.</p>

      <h3>Force 2 &mdash; The 200-day moving average rule for RSU income</h3>
      <p>For RSU income calculation, Fannie Mae uses the <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">200-day moving average</a> of the underlying stock price; <a href="https://guide.freddiemac.com/app/guide/section/5303.4" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Freddie Mac</a> uses the 52-week average. Both methods smooth volatility but produce different qualifying numbers, especially for tech or growth-company executives where stock prices move sharply. The choice of which agency to underwrite under can swing qualifying income by 15&ndash;30%. We choose the favorable agency interpretation when both are available.</p>

      <h3>Force 3 &mdash; Golden handcuffs: unvested equity as a mobility tax</h3>
      <p>Most SVPs and VPs sit on $500K&ndash;$3M of unvested RSUs at any moment. Leaving the company forfeits this unvested equity unless the new employer covers it with a sign-on grant. This creates "golden handcuffs" affecting both job mobility and mortgage timing. Many SVPs time external moves around major vest events to minimize forfeit; we coordinate the mortgage timing with the vest-event calendar so the qualifying picture is optimized.</p>

      <h3>Force 4 &mdash; Garden leave and non-compete clauses</h3>
      <p>SVP and VP employment agreements often include garden leave (paid time-off between roles) and non-compete restrictions (typically 6&ndash;12 months post-departure). These don&rsquo;t directly affect qualifying income, but they create gap periods where W-2 income drops or stops while the executive is restricted. We&rsquo;ve seen lenders mis-categorize garden leave as unemployment when in fact it&rsquo;s contracted continuing comp documented in the separation agreement.</p>

      <h3>Force 5 &mdash; 401(k) catch-up contributions and supplemental plans</h3>
      <p>SVPs and VPs over age 50 can make catch-up contributions to 401(k) plans under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/plan-participant-employee/retirement-topics-catch-up-contributions" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS retirement catch-up rules</a>. Many also participate in supplemental executive retirement plans (SERPs) that effectively extend 401(k) limits. These don&rsquo;t directly qualify as income, but they reduce W-2 reported wages while preserving actual cash flow. We document the relationship between W-2 box 1 and actual cash compensation so underwriters don&rsquo;t mistake aggressive retirement saving for low income.</p>

      <h3>Force 6 &mdash; Multi-state tax allocation</h3>
      <p>Many SVPs live in one state and work at a corporate HQ in another, with RSU vest income subject to multi-state allocation under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/861" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 861 source-of-income rules</a>. State tax allocation creates W-2 reporting complexity. Lenders unfamiliar with multi-state corporate comp often double-count or under-count state-source income. We coordinate with the executive&rsquo;s tax advisor so the W-2 and state K-1 reconcile cleanly before underwriting.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

