  <!-- ============ H2 #9: 25-FAQ SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto var(--s-8);">
        <div class="eyebrow">09 &middot; SVP / VP mortgage FAQs</div>
        <h2>SVP / VP mortgage questions, answered.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-cross-links" style="margin-bottom: var(--s-10); padding: var(--s-6); background: var(--paper-warm); border-left: 3px solid var(--blue);">
          <p style="margin: 0 0 var(--s-3) 0; font-family: var(--serif); font-size: var(--text-md); font-weight: 500;">More <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">SVP / VP mortgage</a> resources at Stairway</p>
          <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: var(--s-5); font-size: var(--text-sm); line-height: 1.7; list-style: none;">
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/">All corporate executive mortgage programs</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/c-suite-executive/">C-Suite executive mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/director-band/">Director-band mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/pre-ipo-equity-holder/">Pre-IPO equity holder mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/relocating-executive/">Relocating executive mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/jumbo-loan/">Jumbo loan program details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/conventional-loan/">Conventional loan program details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/">Start your SVP/VP mortgage pre-approval</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can a newly-promoted VP qualify for a mortgage on RSU income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Not on the new RSU grant. Fannie Mae requires 12 months of time-based RSU vest history before counting the income. Newly-promoted VPs typically qualify on base + prior Director-level W-2 history with bonus, or bank-statement Non-QM. Once the first vest happens and 12 months pass, refinancing with the new income is the standard play.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does Fannie Mae calculate RSU income for SVPs?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Same methodology as for C-suite: take the dollar value of vested shares over the trailing 12 or 24 months, valued at the <strong>200-day moving average</strong> of the company stock price. Divide by months in lookback for the monthly qualifying figure. Add to base salary plus bonus 2-year average for total qualifying income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My annual cash bonus is large but variable. How is it treated?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">With a two-year history, your bonus qualifies on the two-year average under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>. Documentation includes the W-2s showing actual amounts, your employment letter with the bonus formula, and comp committee minutes if available. A declining trend triggers downward adjustment; a growing trend cannot be projected forward (the 2-year average is the ceiling).</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What&rsquo;s the difference between RSU and PSU qualifying requirements?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Time-based RSUs (vest just by staying employed) require 12 months of history. Performance-based PSUs (vest only if performance metrics are hit) require 24 months because timing and value are less predictable. Most SVP/VP grants are a mix of both; we document them separately.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company stock has declined sharply. Does that affect my qualifying income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; potentially significantly. Fannie Mae guidelines require conservative recalculation if year-to-date RSU income is more than 10% lower than the prior year. We can sometimes pivot to <a href="https://guide.freddiemac.com/app/guide/section/5303.4" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Freddie Mac&rsquo;s 52-week average</a> if it produces a better number, or use the bank-statement method.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I have unvested RSUs that I don&rsquo;t want to forfeit. Can I time my mortgage around a vest?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Sometimes &mdash; not always. The trailing 12-month vest history is what matters, not the timing of the most recent vest. But if you&rsquo;re close to a major cliff (e.g., 4-year graded vest with year 1 cliff approaching), waiting until after the cliff gives you a much larger trailing-12 income for qualifying. We map your specific vest schedule against the qualifying window.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use a pledged-asset loan to avoid liquidating my company stock?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes. Pledged-asset (or securities-backed) loans allow you to pledge a portion of your portfolio as collateral, often with $0 down and competitive rates. The benefit: you don&rsquo;t liquidate concentrated stock to fund down payment. The risk: a margin call if the stock drops significantly. We model the loan-to-value scenarios with you.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What about ESPP discount income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">ESPP discount (typically 15%) is reported as W-2 wage in the year of qualifying disposition under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc427" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRS Topic 427</a>. It adds to your W-2 box 1 figure. We document the ESPP participation history; with a multi-year pattern, the discount counts as recurring comp.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering a move to a competitor. How do unvested RSUs affect my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Forfeiting unvested RSUs reduces your future qualifying income unless the new employer covers them with a sign-on grant. If you&rsquo;re close to closing on a home, finish the mortgage on your current employment first &mdash; underwriting completes on current income, not future. If the new role has higher cash + sign-on, that may work better. We model both scenarios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Does my company need to be publicly traded for RSU income to count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally yes under standard Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac rules. Public-company RSUs have a public stock price for the 200-day MA. Private-company equity is generally not eligible for conventional qualifying &mdash; see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/pre-ipo-equity-holder/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pre-IPO Equity Holders sub-page</a> for that case.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need to provide?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically: two years of W-2s, two years of federal 1040s with all schedules, RSU grant letters (all active grants), vesting schedule from your equity platform (Shareworks, Carta, E*TRADE), brokerage statements showing vested share value, employment agreement including bonus formula, comp committee letter for most recent comp adjustment, and recent paystubs.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can my spouse&rsquo;s income combine with mine?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes. Co-borrower files combine W-2s, equity vest, bonus, and 1099 from both spouses. Dual-executive households or SVP + professional spouse combinations routinely support $2M&ndash;$4M+ purchases.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates different for SVPs and VPs?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Not formally &mdash; but practically often yes. SVP/VP files often qualify for the best tier within conforming or jumbo because of strong credit profiles and high reserve balances. We shop multiple lenders to find the optimal rate for the specific file structure.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My LTIP cycle just paid out. Does that help my qualifying income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">A single LTIP payout doesn&rsquo;t qualify as recurring income &mdash; lenders treat it as one-time. With a two-cycle (6-year) history of LTIP payouts, it qualifies under Fannie Mae variable-income rules. We document the LTIP plan formula and historical payout pattern. If you have a single payout, time the mortgage to capture the cash position rather than the income line.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does garden leave affect my mortgage application?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Garden leave is contracted paid time-off between roles, typically 6&ndash;12 months. The income continues during garden leave under the separation agreement, but some lenders mis-categorize it as unemployment. We document garden leave income via the separation agreement and the payroll records, ensuring it&rsquo;s recognized as continuing W-2 income.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What if I&rsquo;m about to be promoted to C-suite?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">If a C-suite promotion is imminent, time the mortgage close after the promotion to capture the larger comp. If you&rsquo;re close on a home and the promotion hasn&rsquo;t formalized, complete the mortgage on current SVP income; refinance later when the new comp is documented for 12 months.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company is being acquired. What happens to my equity comp?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on the acquisition structure: (1) Acceleration of unvested RSUs creates one-time W-2 spike; (2) New retention RSU grant from acquirer starts new 12-month vest clock; (3) Severance if exited counts as continuing income for the contracted period. We model the full picture before quoting; for senior SVPs with change-in-control provisions, see also the <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/corporate-executives/c-suite-executive/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">C-Suite Executive sub-page</a>.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I buy a primary residence and a vacation home simultaneously?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, if reserves and DTI permit. SVP buyers often combine primary + vacation home or primary + rental. Each loan must qualify on its own merits but they can close concurrently. We coordinate the dual-close process so timing aligns.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What loan amount can I qualify for at $600K total comp?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Rough estimate: $350K base + $200K trailing 12-month RSU vest (200-day MA) + $80K bonus 2-year average = $630K annualized qualifying income. At 43% DTI and current jumbo rates, that supports total monthly housing of roughly $22,500. That maps to a $2.5M&ndash;$3.2M mortgage depending on rate, taxes, insurance, and other debts.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Does my 401(k) employer match factor into qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Not directly as qualifying income. The 401(k) match shows on W-2 box 12 and is deferred comp. Lenders consider it in net-worth, reserve, and asset-strength calculations &mdash; it supports the overall financial-strength narrative without being part of monthly qualifying income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What about non-compete clauses in my employment agreement?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Non-compete clauses don&rsquo;t affect mortgage qualification directly &mdash; they affect post-departure mobility. If your employment agreement includes a 6&ndash;12 month non-compete, it doesn&rsquo;t change your current qualifying income, but it does affect the gap-period income picture if you&rsquo;re considering a move. We model both scenarios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My base salary is $400K but my total comp is $900K. Why won&rsquo;t the bank count it?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">The base alone is what shows on the paystub. Lenders trained on W-2 underwriting often stop reading there. The other $500K (RSU vest, bonus, LTIP) qualifies but requires the lender to know what documentation to ask for. That&rsquo;s the entire reason this sub-page exists &mdash; we know how to read the rest of the file.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use a pledged-asset loan and have the cash sit in stocks?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; that&rsquo;s the standard pledged-asset structure. Your brokerage account stays invested; a portion (typically 100&ndash;150% of the loan amount) serves as collateral. If the portfolio drops below the maintenance threshold, you&rsquo;d face a margin call requiring additional collateral or partial paydown. The trade-off: market exposure preserved at the cost of leverage risk.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 60&ndash;90 days before you intend to make an offer. SVP/VP files take longer than standard W-2 files because of the equity comp documentation, bonus formula verification, and sometimes multi-state allocation. Starting early prevents close-of-escrow surprises.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m on a promotion track for SVP next year. Should I wait?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on the home you want and rate environment. If you&rsquo;re comfortable with your target home at current VP income, close now and refinance after promotion. If the target home requires the promoted comp, wait and time the mortgage 12&ndash;13 months after the SVP role start (so the new RSU has 12-month vest history). We model both scenarios with you.</div>
